EXT. DAWES FARM, PORCH - DAY

One black SUV waits in the drive, washed this time. A young WHITE HOUSE AIDE in a good coat stands at the bottom of the porch steps, holding a phone out flat on his upturned palm.

On the porch: PEG, arms crossed. DANNY beside her, sleeves rolled.

MARWANI (V.O.):
(from the phone, warm)
Mrs. Dawes. I hope I find you well. Is the Commander home?

PEG:
He's out.

MARWANI (V.O.):
Of course. Mrs. Dawes, the country is about to share a difficult, beautiful day, and the President — I — would rather share it whole than divided. There are men, I'm told, for whom the past fifty years were a wound. Your husband trained for something that was taken from him. I cannot give him back the years. But I can give him the rest.

Peg says nothing. The aide's arm is getting tired.

MARWANI (V.O.):
The pension, made whole — that's done, as a gesture. The record, amended: Apollo Eighteen entered into the rolls with his name on the crew. Flown status, conferred by executive order — the title, the wings, the history. All of it, Mrs. Dawes. On one condition. Unity Day passes undisturbed — and your husband watches it at home. On his porch. Visibly. Where the country can see a great American at peace with a new world.

Wind in the shelterbelt. Peg looks at the phone on the young man's palm.

PEG:
I'll pass it along if he phones.

MARWANI (V.O.):
Mrs. Dawes—

PEG:
You have a good day now.

She goes inside. The screen door claps. Danny stays a beat longer, looking at the aide, then follows her in. The aide is left holding his own phone out to a farmhouse.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD, NEBRASKA - NIGHT

Joss's truck on a high section road, tailgate down, a wire antenna run from a mast clamp to a fencepost. Joss works a morse key by red flashlight, a paper of cipher groups taped to the tailgate. Danny leans on the fender, watching the sky.

JOSS:
Pass is six minutes. It's enough.

He keys. Stops. Listens to the hiss.

INT. CRATE D - NIGHT (LOW EARTH ORBIT)

The amber light. Morse, thin and far, ticking in Cricket's earpiece. He copies letters onto his pad, steady, no expression.

The pad fills: PENSION WHOLE. RECORD AMENDED. FLOWN STATUS. EXEC ORDER. CONDITION: HOME ON PORCH UNITY DAY. VISIBLE.

Cricket looks at the word VISIBLE a moment.

He knocks on the crate wall: two — two. From crate C, two — two back. From B. From A.

Then he takes the key wired at his hip and sends, short and even.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD - CONTINUOUS

Joss copies onto the tailgate paper, letter by letter, lips moving. Then he stops keying back. Reads it. Reads it again.

DANNY:
What's he say?

JOSS:
(reading)
"Tell him: you can't give back what you never had."

Danny looks at the paper. At the sky.

JOSS:
There's more.

Joss's pencil finishes the last group.

JOSS:
"Dawes out."

Overhead, among all the fixed stars, one moving point of light crosses the dark, west to east, steady.

They watch it go all the way to the horizon.

CUT TO:
